			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="236">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>C.J. Gall&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4946">Thank You for Last Wednesday</a>&rdquo; [July 2014] is possibly the most accurate depiction of marriage in midlife that I have ever read.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Ann Loar Brooks<br>Baltimore, Maryland</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="237">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>My husband and I are retired and together most of the time. We&rsquo;re very conscious of each other&rsquo;s irritating habits &mdash; and of each other&rsquo;s irritation with those irritating habits. I think we&rsquo;re both pissed off at being seventy-eight, arthritic, and poor. At our age we can still hear the siren call of passionate adventure but are unable, or too tired, to heed it. Perhaps we&rsquo;re pissed off at still being alive.</p>

<p>I want to thank C.J. Gall for her essay &ldquo;Thank You for Last Wednesday.&rdquo; I read it about eight times. Now I find it easier to be kind to my husband.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Marcia R. Millington<br>Eagle River, Wisconsin</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

